Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:07 AM; Case called for Review hearing. Prosecuting attorney Charles Patrick Hoffmann in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Davin D Rollins not in court.  Attorney John Paul Marchan in court for Davin D Rollins. Atty. Marchan notes he was informed by the bailiff that the defendant is out of the jail, with no explanation.  Atty. Marchan advises the court he and his client's position is that they are in-line with Dr. Bruett's last report with a finding of competent to proceed, and he has filed a letter with advising that as well.  Court notes it has received and reviewed Atty. Marchan's letter filed on 08/09/2022.  Atty. Marchan just asks the matter be set over for 10 days to locate his client and be sure he can be present to address all of this on the record.  State has no objection, also noting their position is also in-line with Dr. Bruett's findings as well.  Atty. Marchan also notes that a new competency evaluation was ordered in this matter, 21CF176 & 22CF1184 and is asking that order be withdrawn given the circumstances.  Court will withdraw the most recent order for competency evaluation and will adjourn for continued review hearing.  Court will maintain the previously scheduled review hearing set for 8/29/2022 at 8:30.
